# Mini design: Dependency Management in OTel Engine

#### Author: [Bejal Lewis](https://github.com/blewis12)

# Context

As it stands, the Alloy project currently contains minimal modules (Alloy, Tools, and Syntax) \- and when it comes to managing dependencies we mostly concern ourselves with Alloy’s `go.mod` file. Alloy's `go.mod` file has many `replace` directives. These were added over time for various reasons \- like to point a dependency to a patched private fork or unreleased commit before upstream fixes were available, and generally ensuring compatibility among imported components. It might also be the case that upstream components have to solve their own dependency hell issues with `replace` directives, which Alloy does not inherit \- thus we need to copy over the replacements to our own `go.mod` file.

However with the OTel engine, the build process will change: we now build from a Collector module generated from an [OCB](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/collector/custom-collector/) manifest (i.e. our “Alloy OTel distro”). This new Collector module will import the Alloy module and combine the new OTel engine functionality with existing default Alloy engine functionality as part of a single process (refer to [proposal 1 in this design document](?tab=t.yyhz3lrrzf4j#heading=h.afy5rs7781h8) and see the PoC [here](https://github.com/grafana/alloy/compare/basic-otel-engine-and-extension-poc?expand=1)), exposing `otel` (OTel engine) in addition to `run` (Alloy engine) as a subcommand to the CLI.

In addition to the new Collector module, we will also be introducing a third Alloy Engine Extension module which serves as a bridge between OTel engine and Alloy engine. OTel extensions are modules by definition, just like other components \- so introducing another module is less of a decision than a necessity. To make matters more complicated, the modules are all interlinked: OTel engine imports Alloy and the Alloy Extension, and Alloy Extension itself imports Alloy.

# ![][image1]

We are now faced with the issue that we want all dependencies to be aligned across the modules in order for the final build to be what we expect, and match what is built when we build modules independently. Luckily, the Collector and Extension modules should not bring in too many dependencies that we don’t already have. But we will need to ensure that the `replace` directives for shared dependencies are included in all modules.

Another factor that we need to consider is that the Collector module is built from an OCB manifest, which itself generates the code and `go.mod` file for that module. The OCB manifest exposes the ability to define `replace` directives for this very reason \- which will include the directive in its output `go.mod` file. Our solution will also need to fit into the code generation portion of the solution.

# Goals

* Ensure that `replace` directives for shared dependencies are aligned across `go.mod` files
* Ensure that there are no clashing `replace` directives across `go.mod` files
* Make it as simple as possible to understand what is being replaced and where
* Make it as frictionless as possible to edit replace directives across the project

# Non-Goals

* Managing library versions *outside* of `replace` directives. If Alloy requires dependency X version 0.25.0 and the Collector requires dependency X version 0.27.0 \- then the final version included in the build is selected by [MVS](https://go.dev/ref/mod#minimal-version-selection)

# Proposal 0 \- go.mod/builder.yaml Files Are Managed Manually

This would mean having three `go.mod` files, and an OCB manifest that generates one of said mod files, managed separately. One would need to manually ensure that `replace` directives applied to one module are reflected accurately in the others.

**Pros**

* Does not require additional tooling, and therefore unintrusive

**Cons**

* Manual duplication across modules means more effort and higher likelihood of mismatches/clashes
* Harder to diagnose when dependency issues arise
* Replace directives need to also be manually added in the OCB manifest and not the generated `go.mod` file, which isn’t that intuitive

# Proposal 1 \- Defined Replaces in Separate YAML File (Recommended)

![][image2]

We could define our replace directives, across all modules, in a single YAML file with metadata. We could have tooling that reads this and generates replace directives for `go.mod` and `builder-config.yaml` files. Each replacement also contains attached metadata like `comments`, which will also be part of the generated code.

There is an [existing PoC](https://github.com/grafana/alloy/compare/main...blewis12/embed-alloy-in-collector-generate-dependencies-from-shared-yaml) of this approach that is built on top of the OTel engine PoC linked at the start of this doc. However, it might be simpler to look at how this would look on top of Alloy as it currently stands in [this PoC](https://github.com/grafana/alloy/pull/4862).

The following diagram breaks down the sequence of events to make it a bit easier to understand

![][image3]  
Ultimately, the tool itself is relatively “dumb” \- it will copy replaces from a single source of truth to specified mod or builder files. This is also pretty much what the OCB does to address the same issue encountered in the OTel ecosystem: multiple OTel Collector components can reference clashing library versions or make their own replacements, the OCB exposes the `replace` yaml field so that the user can define their own replaces that will automatically be applied to the final `go.mod` file and applied to all upstream components pulled in as part of the build.

It is also worth adding that having an unnecessary replace directive doesn’t cause build failures in a module. If we add a library `replace` directive to a module that does not require that library, `go mod tidy` doesn’t clean up that replacement per se, but it doesn’t complain or cause failures either. In theory we could just duplicate all replacements across all modules.

**Pros**

* Having everything in one file would enable us to detect if the replacements are required/missing in a certain module or if there are conflicting definitions without having to cross reference across modules
* YAML means we can define replacements in a format (OCB, go.mod etc) agnostic manner
* Having a metadata/comment field is also quite nice, it means that folks must understand why they are replacing a dependency before adding it to the file. We could choose to extend this with other metadata as well (e.g. date added)
* In general, this sort of tooling is extendable. We could go further and attempt to define the library versions themselves across all modules ([Joe Harvey](mailto:joe.harvey@grafana.com) has already been ideating on that) \- we’d probably need to extend the OCB to make that work and it’s out of scope for now, but it’s something we could think about if we choose to go forward with this
* Easily removable. Outside of the tooling itself, the `go.mod` files should look the same as if they were edited manually. We could just remove the tool if we feel it’s not serving us
* Consistent replace statements across modules will ensure consistent behaviour across those modules. I.e. if a user uses version X of Alloy, we will know for certain that version X of the Alloy OTel extension behaves the same as the corresponding Alloy version.

**Cons**

* Even if the tooling itself is not that complicated, it’s still tooling. That means a learning curve for those onboarding to the project \- folks need to understand that `replace` directives are defined in a single file and generated
* Similarly, it would be extra tooling to maintain

# Proposal 2 \- Use Go Workspaces (Rejected)

![][image4]  
[Go workspaces](https://go.dev/ref/mod#workspaces) are intended to make dependency management easier in multi-module projects. Workspaces are aware of dependencies across modules and attempt to resolve them in a compatible manner (MVS). One can add a `go.work` file to a project and point to multiple modules which will make up the workspace. Go `build` will use MVS to create a unified dependency graph amongst all modules and use the calculated dependency versions when running locally. One can also define `replace` directives in the `go.work` file which will apply across all modules.

Go workspaces seem to be more designed for **local** development. Moving `replace` directives into the workspace file will not propagate these to the `go.mod` files, and so building modules independently outside of the workspace context would yield different results if the `mod` files are not appropriately updated to reflect the workspace file. Similarly, OCB is also not aware of the workspace environment \- so `replace` directions would not be reflected in the manifest itself even if they are picked up locally in the workspace context. Feedback from other teams on workspace usability was [not so positive](https://raintank-corp.slack.com/archives/CMSUYD6H3/p1762162954204339), who developed extra tooling to make workspaces work for their use case. Ultimately, I don’t think workspaces are intended to solve the problem at hand.

# Proposal 3 \- Use alloy/go.mod as source of truth (Rejected)

Most of our dependencies come from the Alloy project, which both the Collector and Extension import. This proposal explores the possibility of using Alloy’s `go.mod` file as the source of truth for `replace` directives and introducing tooling that will copy over those `replace`’s to the OCB manifest as `go.mod` files of other modules.

**Pros**

* Alloy developers can continue working as they do (paying attention to the main `go.mod` file) whilst we handle propagating necessary dependency versions to other modules in the background-ish


**Cons**

* This only deals with ensuring that alloy dependencies are properly propagated to the extension and collector. It does not allow for replace directives to be copied from say, the Alloy Engine Extension to the Collector `go.mod/builder.yaml` files
* It also doesn’t have a way of dealing with metadata (ie comments, or some sort of signifier where this replace came from and why)
* This feels like it introduces tooling that cannot do much beyond copy and paste, there’s not much flexibility here. It might just be simpler for developers to manually do this

# Proposal 4 \- Use dep-sync Tool (Rejected)
[Dep-sync](http://google.com/url?q=https://github.com/grafana/go-depsync&sa=D&source=docs&ust=1763314566727771&usg=AOvVaw2qyGhckC7ajvBPa8dAwQN9) can be used to point to a go.mod file (child), and specify a certain dependency (parent) within that mod file. Dep-sync will then calculate all shared dependencies and what version each module brings in. It then outputs a “go get” command that can be run to pull in the parents dependency versions. Note that this sync goes one way, parent \-\> child. It doesn’t support multi-way syncing or use any reasoning to pick a certain version to sync to.

Although this tool could potentially be further extended by us, it doesn’t address the issue we want to solve and would probably take quite a bit of modification to do so.

# Proposal 5 \- Monorepo (Rejected)

We could have a shared go.mod file and glub everything into a single module. It would mean that all dependencies are streamlined in a single mod file. However, I’m not sure if this is even possible with the builder setup \- the code generated there also means that the `go.mod` file is generated by the `builder-config.yaml`. Even if we somehow finessed a shared `go.mod` file between the modules in the Alloy project, we can’t create a true monorepo as our Alloy collector distro is itself built on top of modules that are pulled in from OCB.

This would also mean that the release cycle of all the previously separate modules would be tied together, which doesn’t feel reasonable for a project like Alloy.

# Comments

[blewis12](https://github.com/blewis12) I personally feel like Proposal 1 is a good combination of simplicity and usefulness. Although it introduces extra tooling, the tooling itself does not do so much and could be implemented in a way that is modular/extendable. One of the issues I personally see with replacements in `go.mod` currently in alloy as well is that they are unstructured. One can leave a comment or relevant links…or not. Adding metadata fields encourages more thought behind `replace` directives. Additionally, with the new Collector module, we’d be defining replacements both in YAML in the OCB manifest as well as multiple `go.mod` files \- I think it’s conceptually much easier to have this centralized in one file

[thempiotr](https://github.com/thampiotr) \+1 to Proposal 1\. I think that this decision is something that is also quite easy to change in the future as it’s not user-facing and breaking changes to the workflow would only affect engineers working on the codebase and a few in-flight PRs we have.

[pdotev](https://github.com/ptodev) I like proposal 1, mostly because it ensures consistent behaviour of all the Go modules. Otherwise there’s a chance that some replace statements differ, which could then mean that behaviour also differs.
